      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver passes standard benchmark cases (lid-driven cavity, Poiseuille flow) at documented convergence rates.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 vendor verification suite includes lid-driven cavity, backward-facing step, and rotating reference frame benchmarks. Published observed orders of accuracy are consistent with theoretical rates. Gradation 2 requirements are satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Richardson extrapolation or GCI analysis across at least three systematically refined meshes; GCI < 5% on hemolysis index QoI.",
      "rationale": "Three systematically refined hexahedral-dominant meshes (4.2 M, 11.8 M, 31.4 M cells; refinement ratio r ≈ 1.41) were generated. GCI on the scalar hemolysis index was 3.2% between medium and fine meshes, satisfying the < 5% criterion. The fine mesh was selected for all production runs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, fluid temperature, hematocrit) are documented and traceable to calibrated instrumentation.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experimental conditions are fully documented in Hariharan et al. (2011). Flow rates and rotational speeds were set using calibrated gear pump and tachometer traceable to NIST standards. Bovine blood hematocrit (35 ± 2%) was measured with a calibrated micro-centrifuge. All five operating points are covered."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted hemolysis index compared to experimental MIH values; normalized RMS error < 20% across all operating points.",
      "rationale": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were compared to experimental MIH measurements at all five operating points. Normalized RMS error was 11.4%, well within the 20% acceptance threshold. Trend agreement across the flow-speed matrix is excellent, with no systematic bias observed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI used in validation (NIH, shear stress distribution) directly maps to the COU decision quantity (RH index for worst-case condition identification).",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis and volume-averaged scalar shear stress used in validation are the same quantities interrogated in the COU. The relative hemolysis index RH is derived directly from NIH ratios, so the validation QoI is fully relevant to the COU decision metric."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation geometry, fluid, and operating range are sufficiently similar to COU geometry and conditions to support extrapolation.",
      "rationale": "Validation was performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump, which is the same geometry used in the COU. Fluid (bovine blood at physiologic hematocrit), operating range (2–6 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM), and boundary condition types are directly representative of CPB clinical use. No significant extrapolation is required."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence demonstrated by residual reduction of at least 4 orders of magnitude and stabilization of QoI monitors.",
      "rationale": "All simulations achieved residual reductions of 5–6 orders of magnitude. Hemolysis index monitors were tracked every 50 iterations and showed variation < 0.1% over the final 500 iterations, confirming iterative convergence. Double-precision arithmetic was used throughout."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor; scoped out per project risk assessment.",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment is not required at Model Risk Level 2 for this factor category. The factor is acknowledged and documented as not assessed per the MRL 2 scoping rationale in the project credibility plan."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model form uncertainty is quantified through comparison of at least two physically distinct turbulence closure models and one alternative hemolysis power-law formulation, with sensitivity bounds reported on the COU QoI.",
      "rationale": "Model form adequacy for the hemolysis prediction framework was evaluated through an extensive sensitivity study comparing the SST k-omega and realizable k-epsilon turbulence closures across all five operating points. The two models produced hemolysis index predictions within 8% of each other at nominal conditions, and the trend identifying the worst-case operating point (3500 RPM, 2 L/min) was consistent across both closures. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger and Taskin power-law hemolysis models were both implemented, and both ranked operating points identically in terms of relative hemolysis severity, providing strong indirect evidence that the model form is adequate for the COU's comparative ranking objective. The assessment team also draws on seven years of accumulated institutional experience applying this CFD hemolysis framework to rotary blood pump submissions, during which time predictions have consistently agreed with bench measurements within clinical tolerance bands. Expert judgment from three senior biofluid mechanics engineers, each with over a decade of pump hemolysis modeling experience, was formally solicited and documented; all three concluded that the current model form is fit for purpose for worst-case identification at MRL 2. While a formal third turbulence model comparison and uncertainty quantification interval on the COU QoI per the Gradation 3 protocol were not completed due to project timeline constraints, the convergent behavior of two physically distinct model families and the strong empirical track record of the framework provide a defensible basis for acceptance. The credibility assessment team concludes that the evidence, taken in aggregate, is sufficient to support the COU decision with acceptable residual uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor; scoped out per project risk assessment.",
      "rationale": "Model inputs uncertainty quantification beyond nominal calibration is not required at Model Risk Level 2 for this COU. Documented per credibility plan scoping decision."
    },
    {
